    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1987-07-17T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1987-07-17T16:00:00-05:00" n="58"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d58">
                <head>58. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d58fn1">Source:
                        Reagan Library, Carlucci Files, Memos for the Record 1987. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Plains</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1987-07-17T17:00:00-04:00">July 17, 1987, 5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Former President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Jimmy Carter</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CFC_1">Frank Carlucci</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Briefing of President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The main purpose of my visit was to brief President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName> on the Persian Gulf. I went through the actual status of
                    our escorting plan, the vote in the <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> and the
                    debate in the Congress.<note n="2" xml:id="d58fn2">Reference is to the <gloss
                            target="#t_US_2">U.S.</gloss> reflagging and escort of Kuwaiti tankers
                        in the Persian Gulf.</note> President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName> was interested in all the details, particularly the vote
                    in the <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> since he had discussed this on his
                    trip with both the Soviets and the Chinese. He seemed mildly surprised to hear
                    that Dick <persName corresp="#p_WVA_1">Walters</persName> had received some
                    positive signals from the Chinese with regard to the embargo resolution. He
                    voiced no criticism of our decision other than to note that he thought our
                    escorting was rather provocative. I assured him that this was not our intent; we
                    were simply escorting <gloss target="#t_US_2">U.S.</gloss> Flag vessels on the
                    high seas, and our ships represented a threat to no one. He did not pursue the
                    point further.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion unrelated to the Soviet Union.]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Moscow</hi>. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    noted that the Soviets had rolled out the red carpet for him.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d58fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> met <persName
                            corresp="#p_GM_1">Gorbachev</persName> in Moscow on July 1.</note> Like
                    everyone else, he found <persName corresp="#p_GM_1">Gorbachev</persName>
                    impressive. He <pb facs="0304" n="267" xml:id="pg_267"/> thought that <persName
                        corresp="#p_GM_1">Gorbachev</persName> was at a crossroad on the arms
                    control issue. He was debating whether it was in his interest to make an
                    agreement with <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Ronald Reagan</persName> or to wait
                    until the next president. I noted that <persName corresp="#p_GM_1"
                        >Gorbachev</persName> had commented to <persName corresp="#p_GR_1"
                        >Gandhi</persName>
                    <note n="4" xml:id="d58fn4">Indian Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_GR_1"
                            >Rajiv Gandhi</persName>.</note> that it would be in his interest to
                    deal with <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1">Ronald Reagan</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> thought that that might well reflect
                    his thinking but he still hadn’t fully made up his mind. When I noted that the
                    Soviets were throwing up essentially false obstacles on <gloss target="#t_INF_1"
                        >INF</gloss> (100 in Asia and the Pershing 1–A’s) <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> did not disagree. In fact he said he
                    told the Soviets this. When he mentioned the 100 in Asia, pointing to the
                    problems that this created for the Japanese and the Chinese, the Soviets
                    responded with a smile, “we don’t want to put all our cards on the table at
                    once.”</p>
                <p>I told <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> we had not seen much
                    Glasnost in Soviet foreign policy. The Angolans were refusing to negotiate
                    seriously on Cuban withdrawal, a massive arms shipment had just arrived in
                    Nicaragua and the Soviet military presence in Afghanistan was 20,000 troops
                    larger than when <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> left office.
                    Progress in human rights was little more than a trickle.</p>
                <p>Picking up on the latter point, <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                    said he had met with refuseniks during his visit. He was more upbeat on the
                    human rights issue than I was but acknowledged that emigration was still far too
                    low. He noted, however, that a number of refuseniks with whom he had met
                    preferred to stay in the <gloss target="#t_USSR_1">USSR</gloss>.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> asked how we might bring about a
                    thaw in <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>-Soviet relations. I responded that it
                    was very simple. All they needed to do was remove the obstacles to an <gloss
                        target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> agreement and go ahead with the Summit. At the
                    same time it was important that we both make progress with <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss>. This was an agreement that stood on its
                    merits, and we needed to push it. The Soviets had to recognize that <gloss
                        target="#t_SDI_1">SDI</gloss> was going forward. Once they did and stopped
                    trying to kill it via <gloss target="#t_START_1">START</gloss>, we could
                    negotiate with them on a period of stability. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName> did not argue this point.</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is discussion unrelated to the Soviet Union.]</p>
            </div>
